HOOK:
If your child's fever keeps coming back after the flu, stop everything.

BODY:
It's scary when a school-age child's fever keeps returning after the flu.
This could be a new bacterial infection like an ear infection or pneumonia.
It might also be a different virus.
Offer frequent, small sips of water every 5 to 10 minutes.
Use saline nasal drops and an aspirator to clear mucus.
Keep indoor humidity between 40 and 60 percent.
Give fever reducers only if your child is uncomfortable or in pain.
However, watch for serious signs:
Fever lasting more than three consecutive days.
Fever spiking above 101.3 degrees Fahrenheit.
Ear pain or thick, yellow nasal discharge for over 10 days.
Cough that gets worse, wheezing, or difficulty breathing.
Refusing fluids or food.
No urination for over eight hours.
Unusual lethargy, weakness, or not playing as usual.

RELIEF:
If your child has a high fever, trouble breathing, isn't urinating, or is very weak, see a doctor immediately. Otherwise, call your pediatrician to discuss the ongoing symptoms and ask about secondary infections.

